    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="63"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d63">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/7810</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Secretary of the Treasury</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MWG1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McAdoo</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 28, 1918</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I beg leave to acknowledge receipt of your
                    communication, under date of March 19, transmitting a despatch from Ambassador
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">Page</persName> at London, No.
                    8404, dated March 1, 1918, enclosing three-alternative schemes for the extension
                    of the financial blockade suggested in Mr. <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_COT1">Crosby</persName>’s telegram to the
                    Treasury under date of. February 20.<note n="1" xml:id="d63fn1">Telegram only is
                        printed, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_965">p.
                        965</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>As you are aware, the financial blockade has not commended itself to this
                    Department as a step to be taken at the present time, but Ambassador <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">Page</persName>’s communication will be
                    held here until the time seems opportune for considering his suggestions in
                    connection with] the financial blockade.</p>
                <p>In the meantime, I suggest that Ambassador <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">Page</persName>’s attention be directed
                    to the Executive order of January 26, dealing with the regulation of exchange,
                    and to the forms setting forth in detail the information which this Department
                    is now obtaining in regard to financial transactions in the markets of the
                    United States. Copies of these forms were sent to Mr. <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_COT1">Crosby</persName>. The Ambassador will, I
                    think, agree that the information thus obtained will be of great value in
                    checking enemy transactions and in regulating the financial markets of this,
                    country.</p>
                <p>By direction of the Secretary, <lb/> Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LRC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">R. Leffingwell</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Assistant Secretary of the Treasury</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
